---
id: OM-001
subject: Ovarian Tumor Pathophysiology
correct: D
A: Malignant transformation of ovarian surface epithelium due to chronic ovulation
B: Direct invasion from adjacent Müllerian structures
C: Genetic instability in mesonephric duct remnants
D: Neoplastic proliferation from germ cells, stromal elements, or germinal epithelium
E: Somatic mosaicism leading to secondary ovarian involvement
---

A 13-year-old girl presents with progressive abdominal distension and a palpable pelvic mass. Ultrasound reveals a complex cystic and solid ovarian lesion measuring 10 cm in diameter. Tumor markers show elevated AFP and normal β-hCG. Histology demonstrates a yolk sac tumor.  
Which of the following best describes the pathophysiologic origin of this and other ovarian neoplasms in children?

<!-- EXPLANATION -->

Ovarian neoplasms in children arise from one of three principal cellular lineages: **germ cells**, **sex cord–stromal elements**, and **coelomic (germinal) epithelium**. Each lineage reflects a distinct embryologic origin, tumor biology, and clinical behavior. Germ cells derive from the yolk sac and migrate to the urogenital ridge during embryogenesis; abnormal proliferation or failed differentiation of these cells gives rise to germ cell tumors such as dysgerminomas, yolk sac tumors, and immature teratomas. Stromal and sex cord elements, arising from the mesenchymal components of the developing gonad, can produce hormonally active lesions such as granulosa cell and Sertoli-Leydig tumors. Finally, epithelial tumors originate from the coelomic epithelium covering the ovarian surface—this lineage predominates in adults but is uncommon in children.

| **Tumor Class** | **Embryologic Origin** | **Representative Tumors** | **Typical Age Group** |
|------------------|------------------------|----------------------------|------------------------|
| Germ cell        | Primordial germ cells (yolk sac) | Dysgerminoma, Yolk sac, Teratoma | Children/adolescents |
| Sex cord–stromal | Urogenital ridge stroma | Granulosa, Sertoli-Leydig | Early childhood, teens |
| Epithelial       | Coelomic (surface) epithelium | Serous, Mucinous cystadenoma | Late teens/adults |

Malignant transformation is thought to occur via dedifferentiation and unchecked proliferation of precursor cells, often influenced by local hormonal or paracrine factors. While epithelial ovarian cancers dominate in adults, **germ cell tumors comprise approximately 60–77% of pediatric ovarian neoplasms**, reflecting the developmental activity of germ cell lineages during youth. Conversely, sex cord–stromal tumors peak in early childhood, and epithelial neoplasms increase in late adolescence.

